==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foin
<hw>Foin</hw> <pr>(foin)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>fouine</ets>
a marten.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The beech marten
(<spn>Mustela foina</spn>). See <er>Marten</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A kind of fur, black at the top on a whitish ground,
taken from the ferret or weasel of the same
name.</def><mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> He came to the stake in a fair black gown furred and faced with
<qex>foins</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Foin
<hw>Foin</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>foinen</ets>,
<ets>foignen</ets>; of uncertain origin; cf. dial. F. <ets>fouiner</ets>
to push for eels with a spear, fr. F. <ets>fouine</ets> an eelspear,
perh. fr. L. <ets>fodere</ets> to dig, thrust.]</ety> <def>To thrust
with a sword or spear; to lunge.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> He stroke, he soused, he <qex>foynd</qex>, he hewed, he
lashed.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They lash, they <qex>foin</qex>, they pass, they strive to
bore⟦br⟧
Their corselets, and the thinnest parts explore.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Foin
<hw>Foin</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To prick; to st?ng.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Huloet.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foin</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Foin
<hw>Foin</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A pass in fencing; a lunge.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

